      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled solver with documented release notes and regression test suite.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 19.2 is used under an FDA-validated software environment. Version control and regression testing are documented per ISO 9001 QMS. SQA level meets MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Demonstration that the numerical implementation correctly solves the governing equations via benchmark or analytical test cases.",
      "rationale": "Code verification confirmed via lid-driven cavity benchmark and Poiseuille flow analytical comparison. Residuals converge to 1e-6 for all transport equations. Numerical code verification meets required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation or GCI analysis demonstrating discretization error below 5% for primary QoI across at least three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "A mesh sensitivity study was performed using three mesh densities (2.1M, 5.4M, and 11.8M cells). The hemolysis index showed less than 8% variation between medium and fine meshes, and the fine mesh was selected for production runs. Engineering judgment supports that the solution is sufficiently mesh-independent for comparative hemolysis ranking purposes at MRL 2. Formal Richardson extrapolation was not completed due to non-monotonic convergence in near-impeller regions, but overall flow field agreement with experimental velocity data provides confidence in the discretization approach."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions documented with sufficient detail to reproduce boundary conditions in the computational model.",
      "rationale": "FDA generic centrifugal pump experimental conditions are documented in Hariharan et al. (2011). Inlet flow rates, rotational speeds, and fluid properties (bovine blood analog) are fully characterized and replicated as CFD boundary conditions."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of CFD-predicted hemolysis index against experimental measurements with documented error metrics.",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared against experimental values across 5 operating points. Mean absolute error of 12% observed, consistent with published CFD hemolysis prediction accuracy. Relative ranking of operating conditions preserved in all cases."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The modeled QoI (hemolysis index) directly corresponds to the clinical and regulatory decision metric.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the relative hemolysis index (RH) comparing device variant to predicate. This directly maps to the regulatory acceptance criterion RH < 1.0 and clinical hemolysis risk. QoI relevance is fully established."
    },
    {
